animal.description:
""Hi friends! My name is Lane!! I am about 2 years old.
I was found a couple of weeks ago at the Schoharie boat launch. I was a little skinny and had a lot of scabs and boo boos on my head, but my great new friends at Ayres fixed me right up and now I am ready to find a family who will make sure that I never feel like I did wandering alone and with those injuries ever again. I love people that I have met so far, but I may be a little too much for small kids right now. I want to be friends with another dog, but I play really rough and a lot of dogs cannot handle it. So maybe for now, a family all of my own would be best. I really just need someone to love me and continue to teach me what life is and what I am supposed to do. I really want to be the bestest boy. I paw-romise! I am still a young guy - only about 2 years old, even though I look much more distinguished. I got to see the doggy doctor and now all is left is seeing a new family who wants me to be theirs forever. That isn't too much to ask is it? I hope someone sees my soulful eyes and just melts into them and then has to message my friends at Ayres to see how to come meet me! Until then, I will continue to love and play with a full belly and warm blanket. And I will hope that my friends that see this may share me and tell friends about me until my happily ever is found!""

animal.description:
Frosty is a 1 1/2 year old pit mix. What he is mixed with is still unknown to us, but his short tail, and adorable spots sure make him adorable! Frosty is a special boy who has an incontinence issue. Frosty is constantly dripping pee. We have ran many tests and tried all recommended medications without success of fixing the issue.

The following is list of the tests that we have run on Frosty:

Bloodwork CBC & superchem
Urinalysis
Urine culture & sensitivity M130
Second Urine culture & Mic susceptibility was ran at different vet
Ultrasound (results were normal)
Senior profile with heartworm
CT Scan (results were normal)

Frosty was then put on medications, and sadly they did not help.

Now Frosty is in a foster home wondering if the perfect family will ever come for him. We reassure this handsome boy that they will, and when they do it will be meant to be. ?

Frosty is fixed, utd on shots, dewormed, flea treated and microchipped. He is a goofy lovable dog. He has a dominate personality, plays great with other dogs but does have dominate issues and will start fights over food and toys. For this reason we suggest an only dog home.


Although Frosty is a special needs boy, that doesn't make him less deserving of a forever home. Frosty is just patiently waiting for that wonderful family to see him and know that he was meant to be theirs

Help us help this boy find the home of his dreams. ??

animal.description:
Name: Norma Jean (fka Treasure)
Suspected Breed: Rottweiler
Approximate Age: 7 years old
Approximate Weight: 95 lbs
Personality: Sweet and sensitive	
Observations with Dogs: has done well with other dogs
Observations with Cats: not yet tested
Observations with Kids: not yet tested
Currently Living at: DMV-area foster
 
Norma Jean was a staff favorite at our partner shelter in PG County. She came to the shelter when her owner passed away. She is friendly with people and gentle when taking a treat. She would love to warm your house with her love this winter.

Sadly, she will have to undergo heartworm treatment and will need 8 weeks of recovery. This means she will need strict crate rest for a few weeks and only short trips outside to go potty. We can provide guidance and information, but dogs in heartworm recovery tend to be fairly easy to care for as long as they are not super high energy. Heartworm is not contagious among dogs or between species, including cats and humans. She may have a cough the first several days and will need to take 30 days of antibiotics to prevent complications, but otherwise should be easy to care for. She will need to be retested for heartworm in 8-10 months to confirm that the treatment was successful in eradicating all heartworms (treatment rarely fails).

Like most shelter dogs, Norma Jean may need a refresher on housetraining and crate training. We ask all of DC PAWS' fosters to work on both house and crate training with their foster dog.

The adoption fee for this dog is $200. If you are interested in adopting Norma Jean, please submit an adoption application at https://dcpawsrescue.org/adoption-info/adoption-application-dogs/ABOUT US & IMPORTANT DISCLOSURES:

Please note that you must use our official adoption application in order to be considered for adoption. Applying through other sites (i.e., Petfinder) will not work. The following are our applications:

Dog application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=1
Cat application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=6

DC PAWS Rescue does our best to provide accurate and complete information about our adoptable animals. Please note that we cannot make any guarantees about age or breed; we rely upon our rescue partners and their veterinarians to make those assessments. We also cannot make any guarantees about housebreaking and animal temperament, as animals can behave differently through transition and in different environments.

Our shelter partners provide a basic vet screening for each animal we rescue, which includes necessary vaccinations, deworming, microchipping, and spay/neuter (unless the animal is too young or otherwise deemed by the vet to not be a good candidate for surgery). Please note that this is not a comprehensive medical exam and as such, may not identify any and all medical issues, though our goal is to flag any obvious health issues through the basic vet screening. We share all medical records with adopters and are completely transparent about any known issues prior to adoption finalization. 

ABOUT DC PAWS RESCUE

Our rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based dog and cat rescue in the DC area. We rescue locally from Prince Georges County, MD, and from rural shelters in the south (presently Pickens County, Anderson County, and Greenville County in SC, and Raleigh County, WV).

We partner with a local rescuer in Pickens County, SC, who saves adoptable cats and dogs from the three area shelters. For the animals in this rural area, rescue is a critical lifeline, and often the only lifeline. Our rescue partner not only works with DC PAWS to save as many dogs and cats as possible, but she has also established a successful spay/neuter program in the community to decrease the number of homeless and unwanted animals over the long term.

FOSTER AN ANIMAL IN NEED

Fosters make it possible for DC PAWS to save and care for homeless, neglected and abandoned animals! To learn about fostering dogs or cats for DC PAWS Rescue, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/volunteer/fostering/foster-application

SPONSOR AN ANIMAL IN NEED

For any of our animals! Sponsors help us provide critical medical care, food, boarding, and other support for animals facing euthanasia. Individuals who sponsor a dog or cat receive special recognition on the animal's profile. Sponsorships can also be made in honor or memory of a loved one, and you may designate to whom DC PAWS Rescue should provide notice of your gift. Sponsorship levels of $250 and $150 include ""naming rights"" for a future dog or cat (respectively) that we rescue.

To learn more about sponsorship, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/donate/

Max came to us from a shelter in PG County where he was surrendered by his owners due to issues with children. Max was extremely stressed at the shelter (as many dogs are). He was snappy with their staff, but once he made it to a foster home, he finally found some sweet relief! However, he did end up at the shelter because he was in a home with children that were really stressing him out. For this reason, he needs a patient adopter with an adult-only household and no plans for child visitors.

We can recommend a trainer who can arm you with the knowledge of how to read him and help set him up for success. The other benefit of training is to help build trust between you and Max and a deeper bond.

We also cannot make any guarantees about housebreaking and animal temperament, as animals can behave differently through transition and in different environments.

Our shelter partners provide a basic vet screening for each animal we rescue, which includes necessary vaccinations, deworming, microchipping, and spay/neuter (unless the animal is too young or otherwise deemed by the vet to not be a good candidate for surgery). Please note that this is not a comprehensive medical exam and as such, may not identify any and all medical issues, though our goal is to flag any obvious health issues through the basic vet screening. We share all medical records with adopters and are completely transparent about any known issues prior to adoption finalization. 

ABOUT DC PAWS RESCUE

Our rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based dog and cat rescue in the DC area. We rescue locally from Prince Georges County, MD, and from rural shelters in the south (presently Pickens County, Anderson County, and Greenville County in SC, and Raleigh County, WV).

We partner with a local rescuer in Pickens County, SC, who saves adoptable cats and dogs from the three area shelters. For the animals in this rural area, rescue is a critical lifeline, and often the only lifeline. Our rescue partner not only works with DC PAWS to save as many dogs and cats as possible, but she has also established a successful spay/neuter program in the community to decrease the number of homeless and unwanted animals over the long term.

FOSTER AN ANIMAL IN NEED

Fosters make it possible for DC PAWS to save and care for homeless, neglected and abandoned animals! To learn about fostering dogs or cats for DC PAWS Rescue, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/volunteer/fostering/foster-application

SPONSOR AN ANIMAL IN NEED

For any of our animals! Sponsors help us provide critical medical care, food, boarding, and other support for animals facing euthanasia. Individuals who sponsor a dog or cat receive special recognition on the animal's profile. Sponsorships can also be made in honor or memory of a loved one, and you may designate to whom DC PAWS Rescue should provide notice of your gift. Sponsorship levels of $250 and $150 include ""naming rights"" for a future dog or cat (respectively) that we rescue.

To learn more about sponsorship, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/donate/

animal.description: Poland is such an observant boy. He loves to sit outside and watch things go by - people, squirrels, clouds, cars; he's just interested in everything! While indoors, this super cuddly boy mainly wants to drape himself across his human's lap. This loving, goofy dude came to his foster with a possible spinal injury that has affected his walking. He's energetic and appears to be recovering nicely. For now, he is on crate-rest with only a few short, slow walks in the front yard for bathroom breaks. His walking is improving, and he especially walks well on his leash. Once he is healed, he is going to be a great companion for someone who enjoys outdoor activities. Poland seems thrilled to have a home and shows his affection every chance he gets. He's happy to carry around his favorite toy, a skunk that crinkles and squeaks, but rests comfortably in his cage when his people are away. When they're home, he is content to sit at their feet all day long. He's also housetrained so you don't have to worry about accidents while you're away! Poland hopes for a home with people he can be near all day who will take him for walks whenever they have a few spare minutes. He'd also prefer not to have to deal with any of those cat creatures. Come meet this lovable boy. He'll want to observe you and then follow you home!

animal.description: Sweet Tortilla is a special lady who needs a human who can provide her love and take care of her. This gentle lady was not around humans for most of her life, and as a result she can be extremely shy, and takes time to warm up to new humans. Once she does, she is a gentle lass who is sweet and learns quickly. She does well when her humans are away and will hang quietly in the house. She also gives good eye contact, with expressive eyes, eyebrows and brow wrinkles. She is starting to come out of her shell in her foster home, and is making good progress. Tortilla is a retired mama who was very dedicated to her pups, but for the moment prefers to be around very chill pups, or would prefer to be the solo dog in the house. She would also thrive in a low-traffic, adults only home. She is house-trained and if taken out three times a day, she will quickly take care of business and walks around the yard. She would love a fairly quiet home that has a backyard where she can learn to stay calm in the yard. Once her foster gave her time to adjust, Tortilla will touch her nose to her foster's hand and give little kisses. She will also allow short pets and seems to enjoy it. She gives good eye contact and responds when she is talked to. She walks on leash, but gets anxious with new surroundings. She is on anxiety medicine to help curb her fears, and she just loves her medication in peanut butter! Given time, patience, and gentle people she will snuggle someday. She responds well to praise and is food motivated. If you have a low-key, patient, and loving home, come meet this sweet and gentle spirit, her expressive eyes will make you melt.

animal.description: Achilles was found as a stray, but he has so much affection for people that we think he may not have always been on his own. He constantly wants to snuggle and when he sees his people coming, he wags his little tail with all his might! He loves to be by your side and will lay his big adorable head on your leg Or lean his whole body against you. His APA! friends rave about his kisses and how speedy and sneaky he is with them. Achilles is great on leash and loves to go on long walks. He's also a very patient guy and is perfectly content to let you stop and chat with people along the way. He's not particularly interested in other dogs and seems to prefer just spending his time with his people, but he has become enamored with playing fetch, if fetch means running around with the ball in his mouth. He hasn't figured out the other half of fetch yet, but we're working on it. Achilles is also working on being the best dog he can be in APA!'s Total Obedience Program. The Total Obedience Program (TOP) is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Achilles has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help him learn skills like sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' and coming when called. Once Achilles successfully completes all the skills on his training plan he will be considered TOP Dog Ready. Achilles is working hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA! staff to continue to build a training relationship with Achilles after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 This easy-going pooch is a joy to be around and can't wait to meet his family. A more loyal companion you'll never find. Come meet him! Follow Achilles on Instragram @achilles_austin

animal.description: When it comes to smarts and physical abilities, 1 year old Oreo is both whip smart and whip fast! As a young Whippet mix, Oreo would love life in a home with a fenced yard where he can run and play to his heart's content... but he would also like to be welcomed indoors as a part of your family. In his short life, Oreo has not known life indoors but he would love to learn... and this kid is a fast learner. Oreo is eager to learn and connect with a family of his own. Oreo is still discovering how to be social with other dogs and may benefit from a mature, social, friendly dog to share his home with. During his behavior test at the shelter, he was happily curious about other dogs but a little unsure how to play! He would benefit from positive reinforcement training to learn new skills and tricks. He would also love to have daily enrichment opportunities, like solving food puzzles or sniffing lots of smells, so that he can use his active and keen brain. Oreo already knows his name, ''sit'', and ''high five.'' Oreo has a lot of energy and can be nervous around new people so he would be best suited in an adult only home, with humans who will give him the time and patience he needs to be his best self. Once he gets to know you, Oreo is a fun pup who listens well and loves to engage with you by showing off his skills! If you're looking for a friend who will blossom into your bestest buddy, Oreo may be just the one for you. Overall, Oreo is a really good boy who deserves the chance to shine - will you be the one to help Oreo be his best self?

animal.description:
Jean-Michel is little brother to Frida from the Artists Pallet Litter.  He is 4 months old, 20 pounds, born in mid September. Based on current weight we can only estimate that he will be medium size as an adult (between 45 and 55 pounds).
More information will soon be provided along with more pictures.  Her breed may include Pit Bull, Carolina Dog, or Mountain Cur according to Bing Dog Breed Selector. He has a mellow but playful attitude.

Requirements include applicant be a minimum of 25 years old, long term renter or home owner.  Previous personal experience raising and socializing large breed dogs will be given priority.

Applications are at karmicrescue.org

What breed is my dog? Please remember we do not complete DNA tests on our rescued pups. If we do not know who the mom or dad is for sure, we guess; we use Bing Visual Search. And, we look at their paws, ears, snout, coloring, and body build. So often, we are not spot on. Mutts are usually more healthy than not. And, remember too that even if you know the supposed dominant breed in your new puppy or adult dog, it does not mean that those particular genes will dominate your dog's personality.

animal.description:
BACKGROUND:  Little Maurice was picked up as a stray with Margaux, after someone witnessed Margaux being hit by a car.  Both were turned over to rescue from the shelter, so that we could provide immediate medical attention to both.  Maurice has had surgery for bilateral "cherry eye," and has healed nicely.  He is currently on medication for heartworm treatment, and can go to  his forever home now with special instructions to remain quiet.  Maurice has been described as a bit of a spaz because he is so high-energy, but he is learning to walk nicely on a leash and to stay quiet when he is in his wire cage.  Maurice is very sweet, but he will need to learn some manners such as not jumping and barking at his water bowl!  
 
ADOPTION INFO:  Maurice's adoption fee is $395.00, which includes a physical exam, all vaccinations, neuter, cherry eye surgery, deworming and any other care received while in rescue.  If you would like to adopt Maurice, please complete an application on our website at: www.HoustonBostonRescue.org   

FACEBOOK:  Be sure to follow our current events and new incoming rescues on our Facebook page at:  Facebook,com/BostonTerrierRescue 

VIRTUAL FOSTERING:  If you are unable to foster in person, but would still like to help, you can become a virtual foster!  For as little as $20,00 a month, you can virtually foster any of our rescues!  More information can be found on our website at:  www.HoustonBostonRescue.org

NOTE:  All of our foster parents and volunteers work full-time, so please respect  their personal time. Our rescues are available to meet once your application has been approved. Thank you for your understanding!

animal.description:
Age: Approx 5 Years Old
Location: Calgary
Breed: Chihuaua
Sex: Spayed Female
Weight: 10lbs
Energy: Medium
Health Notes: Chronic dry eye requires daily eye ointment
Cats: Not Tested
Dogs: Ellie Loves Dogs and needs to live with another dog that will engage with her. 
Kids: Ellie is ok to be around kids, but prefers to live in an adult only home
Adoption fee: $475

Meet little Ellie. This sweet girl can be described as gentle, playful, cuddly, affectionate, loving, and smart. Ellie has come a long way since arriving at her dedicated foster home. Once a scared, overly shy, and reserved girl, she has slowly come out of her shell  with both dogs and humans (once she gets to know them).

In her day to day, Ellie can be found entertaining herself with toys and puzzles, playing with her foster siblings or snuggling up with her foster mom in cozy blankets. She loves toys so much, she will empty the toy basket, cover the floor in her toys and go to town for hours! Ellie is great at puzzles and figures them out quickly, she has even shown her foster siblings tricks on how to find all the treats!

As a very smart girl, Ellie has come a long way with her house training but accidents can happen if she’s not being carefully watched or isn’t let outside often. With consistency, we believe Ellie will master this soon!

Ellie seeks guidance from other dogs and although is friendly with dogs of all sizes, she absolutely adores smaller dogs and wants to have a forever fur sibling of her own. It takes Ellie some time to get comfortable with new humans. It took weeks before she allowed her foster parents to give her pets, but once she realized how good the pets felt she quickly took up cuddling, asking for more pets, giving kisses and even playing with them. Because she is nervous at first, Ellie will require a slower adoption including a few visits with her adopters before starting a trial.

When Ellie arrived into care with RDDR both her eyes were infected as she has chronic dry eye that had not been treated. We quickly got her infection dealt with and her eyes are now feeling good. She requires eye drops administered twice a day for the rest of her life. A bottle of her drops costs about $70 and lasts about 1.5 to 2 months.

Ellie's requirements for her forever home includes:
-Another small dog that will engage in play.
-A patient and loving adopter who will give her the time to adjust to a new home.
-A quiet home with no children – Ellie gets easily scared of fast movements or busy environments.
-A mom or dad who is comfortable administering her daily eye drops.
-Toys, toys, puzzles and more toys! (also lots of treats)

If you are interested in adopting Ellie, please fill out an adoption application at rosierday.com/adopt

The application must be submitted and reviewed before a meet and greet will be arranged.

Please be patient in waiting to hear back from us as the dogs care is our priority and all of our volunteers work as well as run the rescue in their spare time. You should hear from us within 72 hours.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.1yo/ Pittbull/ 40lbs/ Adoption Fee $400Little Angel joined us from Pine Ridge Reservation where she was rescued. Her first year of life, she was tied on a short rope outside and was never given the love she so deserves. She is working on gaining some weight and her skin is becoming healthier with each day in her new home.

It's unfathomable that someone could treat her soo poorly because as she has settled into her warm foster home, she has shown herself to be an absolute lover. She loves to sleep in the chair next to her foster mom during the work day. But then every few hours she realizes she needs some more love, so she crawls up on her mom's lap for some pets and kisses. She is starting to get the zoomies every so often, so she feels safe and relaxed in her new home. With time, we hope she will continue to feel more comfortable and start to become more independent. But for now, she's her mom's little shadow.

She is working on certain manners still, like not jumping up to check out what's on the kitchen counter or up on new people, but she is cat/dog/people friendly, tolerant of baths, loves car rides, and does not chew on anything she shouldn't. She is learning that life is different now and that she will get food on a regular basis, so she will patiently sit when she knows it's meal time. She does appear to be a bit protective of her toys and foster mom around other dogs.

Unfortunately she hates the crate, but she sleeps great on her mom's bed all night long with no interruptions. On the bright side, she doesn't seem to need a crate for potty-training. She had only one accident in the house her first day here (whoops!) but nothing since!

She loves going for walks and will spin in circles with excitement. That excitement leads to her pulling at first, but after that she walks nicely...unless she sees a squirrel; in that case, she is dying to chase it! With some good leash training, these issues could be fixed.

Overall, Angel is an amazing dog who is looking for a family that will be accepting of all the love she has to give.

The adoption fee covers the cost of the animal's spay/neuter surgery, microchipping, FIV/FeLK testing (for cats) or Heartworm Testing (for dogs), deworming and all core age appropriate vaccinations. For the most complete information regarding this animal, and all of our adoptable pets, please ensure you are visiting our website directly at www.RescueCrew.org. You can also access the necessary online adoption application here as well. Thank you.

Tasia will slalom through an outdoor winter wonderland as she chases other pups around the yard, and during breaks will stop to sniff her way back to her human for some pets or attention. She loves long walks to get out her abundant energy, and has been working on leash manners, an education which will need to continue in her forever home. Tasia has been learning how to be goofy like the mad hatter, enjoying toys and marrow bones during tea time. She will close the day's adventures by putting her paws up on the bed asking whether she can join her human for an overnight snuggle session.

Tasia does well in a home with other dogs of any size, ready to make them tweedle dee to her tweedle dum. She has not yet been to a realm with cats or young children, so we are unsure whether a home with either of them will grow or shrink her confidence.

Tasia is a gentle soul, ready to open herself up to new adventures in a forever home filled with kindness, safety, patience and love that will help her bloom into the heroine she is destined to be. Don't be late for a very important date with this sweet girl, apply to meet Tasia at https://rescuecrew.org/adopt-animal-in-need/#adoptionapplication

animal.description:
Meet Gracie. Gracie is around 2 years old and has had a pretty rough life.

Her first owner was diagnosed with cancer and Gracie stayed with her owner until her owner died. She was rehomed after spending nearly a year with her original owner.

Her second owner was diagnosed with cancer and Gracie again stayed with her owner until she died a few months ago.  A family member of the second owner took her for a while but was not able to keep her.  HappiDog stepped in and now 


Gracie is in love with her foster family, even though this is now her 4th placement in 2 years!  She follows the family's teenage daughter everywhere!

We think Gracie will do best in a home with teenage or older kids. She is a bit nervous around younger kids.  She loves older people and she is particularly fond of women. We think all of her previous owners were female.

Gracie does like to play but is content to hang with her person. She is a very petite little girl, weighing only about 8 pounds.

If you are interested in welcoming Gracie into your family, please go to happidogrescue.com and fill out an online application.

Adoption fee is $295.

animal.description:
Nola is a 6-7 yo female rescued from unfortunate circumstances.   She was a chained dog.    She was emaciated with no water or food in sight.  She had a large mammary mass, and vetting found that she was heart worm positive.  As it  turned out she was pregnant delivering 7 pups 2 weeks after rescue.  She didn’t seem to know what petting, ear scratching and hugging was all about when she first arrived.

She has been in foster for a year now and is on slow kill heart worm treatment (last check still pos).  The mass was removed and she was spayed earlier last year. She recently had dental cleaning.

Nola is very smart and learns quickly.  She is house trained, kennel trained, adores taking walks.  She doesn’t get on furniture and doesn’t lick.  She has lived with cats and kittens and with an old chi mix dog with absolutely no problem (except they won’t play with her).  She seems to love every person she meets.

She is full of life and energy and needs a human or furry companion to play with and a place to run.

Our senior dogs are so grateful of a save, permanent place to lay their head.   Are you interested in meeting this perfect angel?    Contact us about a meet and greet.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 11/19/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Laurens Co AC seized
Foster Location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Frida was spayed on 12/29/20. She also had a dental with 3 extractions. Frida is up to date on all vaccines and heartworm negative.
Weight: 16 lb
Height: 13 in
Spayed/Neutered: No

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Frida would thrive in many environments. She is a great companion and easy going pet.

What is my personality like? Frida is a happy dog that would like a person with a comfy lap to sit on. She enjoys sitting in high up places so she can observe her surrounds. She has been around other dogs majority of her life and would be more comfortable with at least one other dog in her home. Frida tends to bark a lot when meeting new people, hearing a car or even at the wind. She will alert her owners to anything out of the normal. Due to this she may not do well in an apartment or where there are neighbors in close proximity. She is a laid back dog and would do great in a home where they have plenty of love to go around! A fence would be recommended in her future home.

Frida loves to sit up high and can often be found on the back of the sofa or up on the grooming table.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Interested

Other tips and tidbits: (11/13/2018 est birthday.) Frida walks well on a leash and is great in a car. She thoroughly enjoyed sitting in the booster seat and watching out the window.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE FOLLOWING:

Miller had a really bad start in life, ending up on a large chain with no house. Miller would break loose every now and then and got hit by a car several years ago. His leg is so badly bent that it grew that way and cannot be fixed. It doesn't stop him from living a normal life. He came to us with mangled fur, most had to be shaved off and had hot spots all over his back and hips. He had no shelter so it was him verses the weather.

Miller is 4 years old, heartworm positive and very leary of strangers. If he loves you, you have a best friend for life, if he doesn't, he will let you know.

Miller loves his foster mom, loves her dogs, and loves protecting her. He comes inside and loves to check on everyone, but then back outside to guard her property. He would make a wonderful livestock dog or a companion dog if you could keep him from interacting with strangers on his own.

We have neutered him, put him on slo-kill heartworm treatment, groomed him, vaccinated him and loved him like crazy.

If you would like more info on Miller, please fill out the online application at www.fots.petfinder.com

animal.description: Miss Kialey is doing well right now. We are hoping to be able to start accepting applications for her in a few weeks. We believe the first diagnosis of Fanconi Syndrome given to her was incorrect. She spent 2 days with our vet and after many tests it appears she is diabetic and has mammary tumors. She was just spayed which will hopefully help her sugar levels as it did with Stevie. She is however still insulin dependent and requires daily insulin injections. After she heals from the spay and is better regulated, the doctor will look at removing her mammary chain (tumors). If the surgeries go well, we are hopeful that Kialey will have many years left with us.

Date into Rescue: 10/20/20
Reason for being in rescue: Lex was found as a stray in Inman SC. The good people who found him advertised and looked for an owner but with no collar/id tag and no microchip, that search was unsuccessful. Lex was listed on several lost and found sites but no one came forward for him.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Lex had horrible dental problems with over 30 extractions. He has a 4 out of 6 heart murmur and has been started on Vetmedin (1.25 my twice per day to support his heart. Cost is approximately $2 per day). With all of the nasty bacteria from bad teeth out of his mouth we're hoping the heart will improve. His mouth has healed well. He also has developing cataracts which dims his vision.
Weight: 12 lbs
Height: 11 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Lex is a gentle little old man looking for a soft place to retire.

What is my personality like? Lex is a super chill old soul. He gets along great with everyone and everything. He's a gentle old guy looking for a quiet place to retire. He does take vetmedin for a heart condition. (Vet port). He lost a lot of his teeth so he would have to have extra care when preparing his food. He lays around and sleeps most of the day. He would love a fuzzy bed and lots of sunshine to warm his old bones. He would need a home with other older dogs as the young's ones would run him over. He doesn't move fast. He will come over and ask for affection and loves to sit on your lap. He loves treats and loves to eat. He couldn't do long walks but would love a yard to just wander and sit in the sun with you.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Estimated birthdate 10/20/09. Please note this is ONLY an estimate. His true age is unknown. He could be older or he could be younger and have had a rough life

animal.description:
MILLIE is such a very, very sweet Beagle girl. She is everything for why people love Beagles. Running down the side of a Millington highway, she was found by a Good Samaritan and turned into the Millington Animal Hospital for lack of a local shelter. The clinic could not keep her, so we agreed to take her into rescue to keep her from being taken to Memphis Animal Services.

Our doctors and staff quickly fell in love with her, just as everyone else has who has had any interaction with her. One of the first things she received at our clinic was a much needed bath that she thoroughly enjoyed. Her ears were infected, so they were cleaned thoroughly and packed with meds to be checked again in two weeks with another ear cytology. Her bloodwork, thankfully, was great, so we wasted no time in spaying her and did dental care to avoid putting her under anesthesia again. As expected, she tested positive for heartworms, but we are already on that with Doxycycline pre-treatment.  She will be heartworm treated before adoption is permitted. Otherwise, she is in surprisingly good health. She has received both a heartworm preventative, required during heartworm treatment, as well as flea and tick preventative. 

Millie is such a loving little Beagle and we are looking for an equally loving family to foster her through heartworm treatment, and that family will be given first consideration for adoption. We call these foster-to-adopt families, and those are the only applications we are considering at the present time for Millie since we never permit adoptions until heartworm treatment and ALL vetting are completed. 

If you are interested in being a part of Millie’s journey to wellness  and be considered as her adopter, we would love to send you our adoption application. We require our fosters to complete the same application as adopters. Please contact Diana at dmoore2003@bellsouth.net if you are interested in Millie.

We should tell you that all of our Beagles are very popular. Please ask to apply only if you are a serious adopter willing to foster her through vetting and plan on completing our adoption application. We are inundated during the pandemic with adoption application requests. We take great care in the placement of our companion animals and work hard to find as near perfect match as possible between our dogs and their potential adopters.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 11/17/2020

Reason for being in rescue: found as a stray locally
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? none
Weight: 25.4 lbs
Height: est 14" at the shoulder

Adoption Fee: $ 200

Fence needed? No but she would enjoy an area to romp and play off leash several times a week

What kind of home would be best for me? Luna is a sweetheart who will thrive in a variety of homes. She would be great for a young family starting out or for a newly retired couple. She is versatile and easy to love. Love you all miss you all stay safe

What is my personality like? Luna is one sweet girl she loves to be petted and cuddled. She is good on a leash and is crate trained. She has gotten along with every dog she has meet and been with. When it comes to food she is not a picky eater she loves all food and treats. She is not shy when it comes to new people. She is respectful at the first meeting.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Sweet and happy.

More tips and tidbits: Estimated birthdate 6/11/20

PUPPY POLICY:
Thank you for carefully considering the addition of a puppy to your family. Puppies can be a joyous experience, but they can also be a tremendous amount of work. Since our goal is to place each of our dogs in forever homes, we are especially cautious with puppies. We like to stress 3 major things when considering a puppy vs. an adult dog: 1) many adult dogs are well bred, well trained dogs who find themselves in rescue through no fault of their own, 2) adult dogs are eager to share their love and bond with their new family, and 3) puppies will always require far more time, energy, and training than an adult dog.

Our ideal puppy adopters are:
-experienced dog owners with a solid record of excellent vet care of their previous pets
-scheduled away from home for no more than 4 hours per day OR have another canine companion already in the home
-stay at home type of people (work at home, home schoolers, retired, etc)

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Welcome Marie Markle to CCPAL Rescue.  She has a big blocky head and we think she may be an American Bull dog with a Heeler is our best guess.  She is really sweet.  She is a nice young dog that we pulled from the local Animal Control.  Many of these spots in Texas are kill facilities and when they fill up they have to euthanize.  We pulled her before that happened.  She is an active girl and will do best with an outdoorsy family.  She would make a great running, hiking or walking companion.   She pulls when she sees something interesting while on leash but she is attentive and wants direction.  She is good with other dogs but she is a bit much from some dogs because of her enthusiasm.  She is social and will be fine as an only dog.  If you have a fenced yard then some of her exercise could be met playing in the yard.  She hasn’t had any formal training so she has skills of a younger dog.  Someone willing to teach her the ropes would be great.  She is in Texas and can be adopted locally or we can work with one of the wonderful transporters to deliver her to Washington, Portland, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Vermont or all along the East Coast.  Her adoption fee is 250 and transport is 185.  Rhode Island and Massachusetts are not states we adopt to because of the regulations imposed by these states. 

Contact Marlene at 210-867-1769 or email to ccpalinquiries@gmail.com if you have questions. Online applications at www.ccpal.info/ See her cute video!!

animal.description:
CHRISTOPHER HAS AN APPLICATION IN REVIEW AND IS EXPECTED TO HAVE A PENDING ADOPTION SHORTLY.

Meet the C pups:: 8 weeks old as of 1/9/21, ranging from 6 to 11 pounds, 6 males, 2 females, Aussie/Pyr/Catahoula mixes.

Available for Adoption!

Christopher is a big time snuggler and is always seeking out affection from his foster family. He gets along great with the other dogs in the home and loves to play with his foster's children! Christopher is working on potty training and doing well with learning basic commands.

These little cuties had a rough start to life and came to us covered in flea dander and scabs. We have treated them and have given them more dewormer and they are settling in nicely in their foster home. They will be working on potty training and basic in home manners to help them succeed in their forever homes. These babies are sweet and playful and ready to find their forever families.

These puppies will require an active family and active lifestyle.

$195 Adoption Fee. 

A $10.00 non-refundable application fee is required to submit your adoption application and will be deducted from your adoption fee if you adopt.

All puppies are dewormed, started on heartworm and flea prevention, and microchipped.

All puppies will be adopted with current, age appropriate vaccines, given by Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue. Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue will provide their puppy series DAPP vaccines, given at 8, 12, and 16 weeks of age.

Puppy adopters will be will be required to bring the puppy back to Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue to receive any remaining puppy vaccines after adoption. 

Puppy adopters will also be required to bring the puppy to our vet for their spay/neuter surgery after they receive their 16 week vaccination. 

The spay/neuter and puppy vaccines are included with the puppy adoption fee.

We have a strict one hour puppy adoption radius, puppy adopters must be within one hour of Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue. Please see our Adoption Radius tab on our website for more info, here:

animal.description:
Meet Major!  Major is a 2 year old, neutered male German Shepherd.  He came to the rescue as a bad neglect case.  He was hit by a car and then abandoned in a cage for 5 days with no food, water or medical attention.  He had a broken pelvis and needed emergency surgery to amputate his tail.  He had a severe wound on his leg with bone exposed.  After much TLC, Major is on the mend and thriving!

Major does well in play groups but is a really rough player.  Whether or not he will do well with another dog in the household will be dependent on how they do together.  He has been around cats and has done very well, as long as the kitty doesn't run.  He absolutely loves squeaky toys.  He is crate trained and house trained, but he does excited pee.  

If you are interested in adopting Major, please email us at therescueboutique@gmail.com

animal.description:
Daisy is a cute 2-year old female Red Heeler/Terrier mix who arrived at the HSOV on January 9, 2021 after she was picked up on Marsh Hill Run Road near Marietta Ohio by a Washington County Deputy Sheriff on behalf of the Dog Warden.  Daisy was wearing a collar but there was neither an id tag nor a dog tag to enable us to locate her owner ... And she was not microchipped.

Daisy has a white short smooth coat with tan markings on her back/hind quarters, a long tail, and a symmetrically-marked face with amber-colored eyes, a liver-colored nose, a slender muzzle, and extra-large erect ears.

Daisy was full of energy when we took preliminary photos as HSOV kennel tech Brad Loyland was taking her back to her kennel after she had enjoyed some fresh air and sunshine on a cool afternoon.  Daisy wasn't ready to pose for boring still-life photos :)

Daisy weighs 37 lbs and is energetic on a leash.

In compliance with the Ohio Revised Code, Daisy will be held for three days so that her family will have an opportunity to reclaim her with proof of ownership.

IF YOU SEE ME HERE, I AM AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION. PLEASE READ MY BIO BELOW TO LEARN MORE ABOUT ME AND HOW TO APPLY TO ADOPT :)

Meet the C pups:: 8 weeks old as of 1/9/21, ranging from 6 to 11 pounds, 6 males, 2 females, Aussie/Pyr/Catahoula mixes.

Available for Adoption!

Cyndey is a playful and sweet little angel who loves to snuggle up when play time is over. She is doing well with potty training and basic commands in her foster home and loves to play with other dogs. 

These little cuties had a rough start to life and came to us covered in flea dander and scabs. We have treated them and have given them more dewormer and they are settling in nicely in their foster home. They will be working on potty training and basic in home manners to help them succeed in their forever homes. These babies are sweet and playful and ready to find their forever families.

These puppies will require an active family and active lifestyle.

$195 Adoption Fee. 

A $10.00 non-refundable application fee is required to submit your adoption application and will be deducted from your adoption fee if you adopt.

All puppies are dewormed, started on heartworm and flea prevention, and microchipped.

All puppies will be adopted with current, age appropriate vaccines, given by Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue. Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue will provide their puppy series DAPP vaccines, given at 8, 12, and 16 weeks of age.

Puppy adopters will be will be required to bring the puppy back to Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue to receive any remaining puppy vaccines after adoption. 

Puppy adopters will also be required to bring the puppy to our vet for their spay/neuter surgery after they receive their 16 week vaccination. 

The spay/neuter and puppy vaccines are included with the puppy adoption fee.

animal.description:
Don't let this pretty, seemingly innocent face fool you! Two year old Chloe is a bundle of energy! Not a mean bone in her body but quite an exuberant pupper. Belly rubs and petting do settle her, She will settle down in a comfy spot. She's very sweet and affectionate, just hyper. Due to her energy, small children are not a good match.

As for other dogs, she's overwhelming to them. She invades their personal space and has no off button. It's pure play, not aggression, but other dogs do not appreciate it. Chloe would do best as an only dog for this reason. Her dream home is an active one where she can wear herself out productively. Cats are a definite no for all the reasons above. 

**If you are serious about adopting , you must head to our website at www.kodisclub.org and submit a completed application . We will not do anything without an app. Due to the small size of our volunteer-run rescue, only the approved adopter may be contacted. It is not first come first served, but the best match. Yes, if you are reading this, the dog is available so no need to check **

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Meet HOMER! Homer is 6-7 years old and weighs 100lbs. Homer came into rescue in horrible condition. He had skin issues, was malnourished, and was very shut down. With the love of an amazing foster Mom, Homer has become a healthy, happy guy who is quite the character! Homer LOVES attention from his humans and expects to be pampered. He demands his daily walks, he is wonderful on leash, and loves to eat. Homer gets along with all the dogs in his foster home but can be an only dog that is spoiled and has his new family's full attention. He is house trained and will let you know he wants to go outside by standing by the door. Homer likes to bark at dusk just to make sure his people and property are protected but is otherwise quiet. Homer can be stubborn and would do best with a Pyr experienced owner. He is also very smart and can open gates and doors. He would love a secure yard to lounge in and patrol when the need serves him. Homer is currently in Texas but can be on the next NW transport.

All our dogs require secure VISIBLE fencing. All current pets in adoptive home must be spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Adoption Fee: $350

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations.

Transport Fee: $300

Transport fee includes the cost of transport plus the Health Certificate required for USDA approved transport.

Adoption applications can be found on our website: www.greatpyrsandpaws.org

https://greatpyrsandpaws.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=5959

Northwest adopter pays cost of transport to independent transport company. Transport is arranged by GPPR.

animal.description:
Gideon came to us from Red Lake Reservation. Gideon is a goofy pup that was found on the run before coming to rescue. He is learning manners on a leash, obedience, and other skills that would make him more acceptable for adoption. He can sometimes be mouthy but generally not rough but he does do it frequently when he doesn't get his way. 
While Gideon is learning proper dog skills he also is recovering from Demodex mange that had him almost nearly bald but thank goodness he has been treated and had 2 skin scrape tests that have been negative, besides having a beautiful chocolate colored coat grow back in. Gideon does have a few scars from the mange mostly noticeable on his nose and bridge of his muzzle. In addition to coming to rescue with mange, Gideon came with a prior injury to his eye that has left it scarred and uncertain if there is any visual abilities of the eye but it doesn't not seem to slow him down, just cosmetically distracting. We have been told at present time it does not appear as though the eye needs to be removed but can not speak for the future. 
Gideon is scheduled in April to be neutered, he is current on vaccines, dewormed, chipped, and heartworm negative. If adopted prior to his neuter date, he will require a spay/neuter contract. If you would like more information or would like to meet him please contact us via email or phone.

animal.description:
Hello, good humans! My name is Aunt May. If you're looking for a goofy and sweet couch potato, your search is over. You found me!

I'm a "perfect angel" (my foster mom said so!) and I would love a lowkey family to call my own. I love to take naps and cuddle on the couch. I would choose sunbathing in the yard over a walk ANY DAY. I would do best in a home where I don't have to climb too many stairs. 

I'm dog-friendly, and I do best with calm dogs who aren't in my face all the time. Any dog who loves to partake in being a snuggle puddle will be my best friend! I haven't been around kids too much, but as long as they are respectful of me I will be just fine. I have some problems with my left eye, so my foster mom gives me drops a few times a day. She says I'm already looking so much better! 

With a great pit bull (that's me!) comes great cuddles. Apply to meet me now!

animal.description:
**If a dog/pup is still listed on petfinder we are still accepting applications on him/her. We will not respond to petfinder inquiries regarding any information already publicly posted.** Please take time to read the information provided and complete an application if interested.** Incomplete applications will not be considered.**

Hi! My name is Jennings! 
I am about 1.5 years old and I weigh around 9 pounds. I am neutered, current on vaccines, microchipped, and on heartworm and flea prevention. I came to my rescue after being abandoned out in the woods with another pup. My foster has worked hard at socializing me as it seems I didn’t have much interaction with people prior to coming to rescue. I will need a quiet, patient home with a physically fenced yard and another confident, like sized pup to play with and show me the ropes. Once I warm up I am the sweetest most cuddly guy and I give lots of kisses! I will require consistent professional grooming. Please list the groomer that you use or intend to use in the, “anything else” section of the application. 
My adoption fee is $425.

Please submit an application if you want to make me part of your family! 
Meet and greets are scheduled with approved adopters. 
Copy the link below and paste it into your browser for an application:

http://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/wACc22HN2JDb60dtb465Z 


Our adoption process consists of an application, and reference checks. We do home visits when a reference check is not enough. You must be at least 21 years old to apply to adopt.
Please fill out all fields as accurately as possible. We will not process incomplete applications. 

Adoptions are made on a best home basis. If two excellent applications come in for the same dog, our policy is first in time, first in line. Our goal is to have the very best home for all our dogs. Our dogs are in private foster homes waiting to be adopted. Due to limited foster space, we are unable to hold an animal to be adopted out at a later time.

Please keep in mind that we do our best to make an educated guess as to the breeds of our rescued pets. In rescue we rarely see the parents of our dogs and puppies, and even when we do, they are usually mixed breeds as well. 

We rely solely on adoption fees and donations to provide care for our rescued animals, many of whom have incurred medical bills that are much higher than any possible adoption fee. The fees received act to help support the organization as a whole, allowing them to continue efforts to rescue animals from high-kill shelters in South Carolina and Georgia.

animal.description:
Lucy is an energetic girl that just recently came to rescue after her family had another little baby and they were concerned with Lucy's energy and safety of their infant. 
Lucy needs a fenced yard and a family with kids over 10 years old since she has a lot of energy and may knock over little ones. Lucy is working on manners and obedience. She is learning crate training and housebreaking. Lucy is getting better with housebreaking with scheduled feedings and routine outdoor time. Lucy does require crating when not supervised as she will chew on inappropriate items (meaning bedtime and when not home)
She does have issues with prey drive and not particularly fond of other dogs but we are trying to work on this issue. She is definitely not recommended with cats, small animals, pocket pets, birds, or livestock. 
Lucy has begun vaccinations, she is heart worm negative, she is dewormed, chipped, and awaiting spay. If adopted prior to her spay, she will go out on a spay/neuter contract. 
Lucy would thrive in an home that is active and can keep her busy, she still has alot of puppy left in her.

animal.description:
Hi everyone, I’m Vito! The nice people  that saved me said I should tell you about myself so I can find my forever home. 

I’m estimated at two years old and am a mixed breed boy of about 50 pounds. I am potty trained, neutered and vaccinated. Yay!

I had a very hard first couple of years so I really need a special home. I am a smart boy who craves companionship and am eager to please my people. I absolutely love being part of a pack so my home must have at least one other dog, preferably of similar size or larger. I have a high prey drive so there should be no cats or other small animals in my home. I can also get overly stimulated and forget all my manners sometimes so I need a home without small children. Safety first!!

I need a strong, confident person. I am a very good boy and I really need structure, routine and exercise. 

I know my perfect home is out there! If you have no little people or animals in your home, at least one other dog (or two!) and can provide a strong lead and structured life...we could live happily ever after together!!

Apply to adopt here: https://www.dogsdeservebetterblueridge.org/adopt

animal.description: Quinn was picked up as a stray on a busy 4-lane highway. She was matted, nails were very long and curled, and she had 3 very large masses on her abdomen. Animal control guessed her age at 8 plus. She is a very sweet little girl her loves to snuggle. Our vet also found bladder stones and her teeth are rotten. In addition, she was not spayed. To date, she has been spayed, had the stones removed and had the mass removed from under her front leg which has made it much easier for her to walk as that mass was a cyst that was full of fluid and kept filling up after it was drained several times. A malignant mass was found at the center. It was described as a slow growing mass and was completely excised. Soon she will have the mammary masses removed and will have a dental to address her teeth. She would do best in a quiet home with a family who will love her and take her for walks. She can be a bit bossey if she is hungry and you are too slow. She would also do well with older, calmer children who will be gentle as she only weighs 15 lbs. She is in foster care with other dogs and cats and does quite well. If you are that special family who will give her plenty of love, tlc, and a permanent home, please contact Rainbow Animal Rescue at rainbowanimalrescueva@gmail.com

Holly is a stunning 1 year old, 45 lb Husky pup. Her previous foster mom states that she is very sweet and loves kids. Holly was around children that were 16 months and 4 years old and did wonderfully. Holly walks nicely on leash. She gets along with all sized dogs and prefers to live in a cat free zone. Shes curious of all the scents on her walks, loves to be outside in the fresh air and loves to run around in the play yard. Were working on sit and down and shes doing very well. Holly would love to have a big 6 foot fenced yard to spend time in. She did remarkably well with house training and made a mild fuss with the kennel but respected it. She is a typical husky that would make a great jogging partner. She just finished training with Second Chance Pups. Come visit with her and youll see how special she is.

Toffee is a very sweet senior gal who loves attention. She came to ARF brokenhearted when her owner passed away. Toffee is housebroken, great with children, cats and other dogs.

Fill out an application at the link below. Find the dog/cat you are interested in and click the adopt button. That will take you to an application. Once approved you will be called for an appointment to meet your possible new family member, or at that time you can meet the other animals as well. https://petstablished.com/public/search/shelter/301551

Adoption fee is $150 which includes, spay/neuter, vaccines, etc, and a free 1 year membership to our 5 acre ARF Park. For other dog questions please email ARFdogs74006@gmail.com

We do adopt out of state, but the adopter must travel to ARF to meet the dog they are looking to adopt. They must have an approved application before traveling to meet the dog. We do allow small dogs that are eligible to fly in the cabin of a plane. We DO NOT allow dogs to travel in the cargo area of the plane under any circumstances. Any dog that is adopted can of course go by personal vehicle. We do not allow dogs to be transported "pony express style" where they are passed from driver to driver.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Lala. I am an adorable medium sized young dog weighing in at about 30 pounds. I've been told that I'm a super sweet girl. In fact, I can be a total lap dog! But mostly I am an active working breed dog and likely more blue heeler than not which means I am smart, active, and able to think on my own. I enjoy playing with toys and with other dogs but my sense of personal space is not that great. If you're interested in someone who is sweet, sassy, adorable, and fun - I might be the girl for you! I must have a home with a fenced yard, another dog-friendly-dog would be ideal, and an experienced dog owner with time to spend on me. Older children, over the age of 10 should be fine, as the smaller oneswell they are way too fun to herd. Cats are fun to herd, too.

 

To adopt Lala visit our website for more details regarding our adoption criteria and complete the easy online no obligation adoption application at www.dsda.org/adopt. 

* Adoption Fees:

Puppies (12 months and under) - $325 (includes tax)

Dogs (over 12 months) - $275 (includes tax) 

 

Qualifications for Adoption: No dog is alike and each dog has different requirements based on breed, age, energy level and life experiences. DSDA is very careful to place our dogs in homes that we believe are the best fit for the dog based on our experience with each dog. All of our dogs live in foster homes which allows us the opportunity to learn about their individual needs. 


	Must be 21 years or older with identification showing present address.
	Must have the knowledge and consent of all adults living in the household.
	Vet checks are required. All resident animals must be spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations and on monthly heartworm and flea/tick preventative (if applicable).
	Must receive proof of pet deposit and lease allowing pets if renting.
	Willingness and capacity to spend the time and money necessary to provide training, medical treatment and responsible care for a pet.
	Applicant is home more than not.
	Any poisonous plants must be removed from the yard before the home visit.
	Home visit is required. For this reason, we adopt locally in the Dallas and immediate surrounding areas.

We have no back story or update for this dog at this time. When we do, it will be updated here. This is all the information we have currently.

HW+ simply means the dog has tested positive for heart worms in our screening process. We utilize what is called the fast-kill method which means we place the dog on antibiotics for 30 days and then administer 3 injections in increments afterward. The cost to treat heart worms is rather steep. However, thanks to our generous donors, we are able to cover that cost for our adopters so long as they go to our veterinarian, Red Rocks Animal Center in Lakewood.

	Adoption fees include vaccines up until time of adoption, microchip, spay/neuter and 1st 30 days of free Pet insurance. We are not affiliated with Pet First pet insurance. (you have to sign up for the insurance or it will not go into effect). 
	Adopters can go to our vet for medical issues that may arise in 1st 3 days of adoption. 
	The dogs in our care are fostered in Colorado, Texas, and New Mexico. While all dogs are picked up during our scheduled times, sometimes transport dates change due to unforeseen circumstances.

**If a dog/pup is still listed on petfinder we are still accepting applications on him/her. We will not respond to petfinder inquiries regarding any information already publicly posted.** Please take time to read the information provided and complete an application if interested.** Incomplete applications will not be considered.**

Hi! My name is Herbert! 
I am about 13 years old and I weigh around 12 pounds. I am neutered, current on vaccines, microchipped, and on heartworm and flea prevention. My foster mom says I am the most well mannered of pups and an easy guy to have around! I love to cuddle and have great appreciation for a soft bed and fuzzy blankets! 
My adoption fee is $325. 

*Herbert is eligible for our seniors program. Our Seniors for Seniors Program offers senior citizens 65 years or older the opportunity to adopt a senior dog at a reduced adoption fee. Adoption application and screening still apply.* 

Please submit an application if you want to make me part of your family! 
Meet and greets are scheduled with approved adopters. 
Copy the link below and paste it into your browser for an application:

http://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/wACc22HN2JDb60dtb465Z 


Our adoption process consists of an application, and reference checks. We do home visits when a reference check is not enough. You must be at least 21 years old to apply to adopt.
Please fill out all fields as accurately as possible. We will not process incomplete applications. 

Adoptions are made on a best home basis. If two excellent applications come in for the same dog, our policy is first in time, first in line. Our goal is to have the very best home for all our dogs. Our dogs are in private foster homes waiting to be adopted. Due to limited foster space, we are unable to hold an animal to be adopted out at a later time.

Please keep in mind that we do our best to make an educated guess as to the breeds of our rescued pets. In rescue we rarely see the parents of our dogs and puppies, and even when we do, they are usually mixed breeds as well. 

We rely solely on adoption fees and donations to provide care for our rescued animals, many of whom have incurred medical bills that are much higher than any possible adoption fee. The fees received act to help support the organization as a whole, allowing them to continue efforts to rescue animals from high-kill shelters in South Carolina and Georgia.

animal.description:
Beethoven is the perfect age for a pit bull at around 4 years old. He is smart, house trained, crate trained and fantastic in the car. He is good on a leash and would do just about anything for a treat or a tennis ball. Beethoven is deaf but that doesn't slow him down. If anything he is more attentive than hearing dogs because he looks to his person for direction. Beethoven knows sign language and is a velcro dog: wherever his person is, that is where he wants to be. Beethoven loves the water and will spend hours splashing in a baby pool. This sweet guy would make a great running buddy or agility dog. Beethoven would prefer to be the only 4 legged member of your family! His favorite spot is on the couch..... UNDER the blankets! Looking for a couch buddy??? Apply to adopt Beethoven today!
Beethoven is neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped and heartworm tested and on preventative. His adoption fee is $175.
To apply to adopt Beethoven, visit www.adoptapitrescue.org/apply
All of our dogs are spayed or neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped and if over 6 months of age, heartworm tested and on heartworm preventative in their foster home.

We require an approved application to meet any of our dogs. We do not have a shelter location and will not arrange a meeting without an approved application.

We strive to make sure the bios provided for our dogs are complete and accurate; we do understand that mistakes happen, however, so if you absolutely cannot find the answer to your question in the dog's bio, you can contact us for more information.

We require a home visit for each dog we adopt out, so we adopt within a 2 hour radius of Dayton, OH. If you are outside of this radius, we encourage you to contact your local rescue or shelter.

animal.description:
*****************************************************************
PLEASE READ THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING
*****************************************************************

--ABOUT JADE--
Jade is a sweet and sensitive girl found as a stray. She likes to take things slow and get to know you before she lets you in, but is so lovable and affectionate when she does! She loves to play with toys, and will carry around her favorites! There hasn't been much structure in her life and she needs some help learning the basics still, like housebreaking and leash walking, but she is very eager to please! She's been happy to welcome her human friends into her kennel for cuddles or tug-o-war. She wants to be the queen of the castle as an only pet in her new home, soaking up all the love. 

Key Notes:
-2 year old spayed female.
-Pit bull terrier mix.
-65 pounds and a healthy weight.
-Brought to animal control when found as a local stray.
-No apartment style or multi-family homes, city living, or busy/loud neighborhoods.
-Has not been around kids yet, but should not live with any younger than 12.
-Should be an only pet.
-No more than 5 hours alone a day; will need a potty and play break.
-Experience with dogs recommended.
-Medium energy; loves to play with her toys and also loves snuggling and pets.
-Not yet housebroken.
-Walks well on leash, but can be strong.
-Shy at first, especially with men, but warms up quickly and is very loving.
-Basic obedience training recommended.

--THE ADOPTION PROCESS--
If you are interested in adopting this animal, please submit an online application. Applications will be reviewed as received. If in our opinion a pet is a good candidate for you, an adoption counselor will contact you to schedule a zoom chat. If you do not hear from us it simply means either the animal has been adopted or we have not received the right pet for you. The application process is at no charge to you and only needs to be completed once as all applications will be kept on file.

Online applications can be found here: www.buddydoghs.com/forms

Check out our FAQ for answers to most questions here: www.buddydoghs.com/faq

Adopters must be at least 21 years of age and a Massachusetts resident.

If you live outside of TX or OK, you will need to contact our organizations Management Team first: managementteam2@yahoo.com. Out-of-state adoptions are considered on a case-by-case basis.

Our organization requires prospective adopters to complete an approval process prior to meeting with dogs in our program. This includes:
*Completion of Adoption Application
*Veterinarian Check
*Reference Checks (non-relatives)
*Home Visit

Our ultimate goal is to screen and counsel potential homes to the best of our ability in an effort to find the most perfect match and fit for their lifestyle.

Please keep in mind that color and appearance of the available dog is last on our priority list, and will have no bearing on adoption placement decisions.

Please refrain from contacting members of our organization or asking about specific dogs/potential matches until after your screening process has been completed and approved.

***$300 Adoption Fee + state-required tax.***
--------------------------------------------------------

ABOUT ROGAN
Rep: Laura - aussie330@aol.com


Rogan is an approximately 1.5yo Aussie that came to us from a shelter after he was picked up as a stray and never reclaimed. He is fully-vetted, house-trained, crate-trained, and does well on a leash.  He is currently located in Bedford, TX and it is required that you travel there to meet him in person to adopt, no exceptions. We do need the entire party to be involved when meeting available dogs, including every family member and dog(s) that currently live in your home.

Rogan is still very new to our program, but so far, he has been a very sweet and intelligent boy.  He does have some uncertainties that make him a big anxious, so a home with children is best.  He does great with other dogs and bonds deeply to "his" people.  He also had a cat-test where he showed a bit too much interest, so a home without cats would be best.

Please check back as we get to know him more!
